/*
:name: lead_or_chain
:type: equiv
:verilog_top: lead_or_chain.top
:pyrope_top: top
*/

// Regression for the line-leading word-operator continuation bug: a long boolean
// chain whose `or`/`and` operators begin the continuation line used to be
// mis-parsed — each leading `or (...)` became a stray `or(...)` call, so the
// result kept ONLY the first term. The two outputs cross the spellings so that
// whichever side (Pyrope front-end OR the shared upass that slang also feeds)
// dropped a term would diverge from its golden:
//
//   out1 : Pyrope = CHAINED (leading-operator continuation)  | Verilog = split wires
//   out2 : Pyrope = SPLIT named conditions                   | Verilog = inline chain
//
// Both outputs are logically the same function written two ways, so the LEC must
// hold only when continuation parsing keeps every term.
pub comb top(sel:u4, x:u8, y:u8) -> (out1:bool, out2:bool) {
  // out1 — the chained form, operators starting each continuation line. This is
  // the exact shape that used to silently collapse to `(sel == 0 and x == y)`.
  out1 =
       (sel == 0 and x == y)
    or (sel == 1 and x != y)
    or (sel == 2 and x <  y)
    or (sel == 3 and x <= y)
    or (sel == 4 and x >  y)
    or (sel == 5 and x >= y)
    or (sel == 6 and x == 0)
    or (sel == 7 and y == 0)

  // out2 — the same kind of wide function, but broken into named conditions and
  // recombined. One condition also spans lines with a leading `and` to exercise
  // that spelling too.
  const d0 = sel == 8  and x == y
  const d1 = sel == 9  and x != y
  const d2 = sel == 10
         and x <  y
  const d3 = sel == 11 and x >= y
  const d4 = sel == 12 and x == 0
  const d5 = sel == 13 and y == 0
  out2 = d0 or d1 or d2 or d3 or d4 or d5
}
